The given matrix corresponds to a projection if it is idempotent, i.e., $A^2 = A$. We can use this property to find the values of a and c. <solution> Let's equate the elements of $A^2$ to $A$ for $A=\begin{pmatrix} a & \frac{15}{34}\\ c& \frac{25}{34} \end{pmatrix}$. Taking the dot product, we get:

\begin{align*}
a & = \frac{25}{34}a+\frac{15}{34}c \\
c & = \frac{25}{34}a+\frac{15}{34}c
\end{align*}

Subtracting the first equation from the second gives:

\begin{align*}
c-a & = \frac{25}{34}c-\frac{15}{34}a \\
34(c-a) & = 25c-15a \\
9a & = c
\end{align*}

Filling a back into the system of equations, we find that $a=\frac{1}{10}$ and $c=\frac{9}{10}$ <end think></think> <answer> $\left(\frac{1}{10},\frac{9}{10}\right)$ </answer>

